Cybersecurity Awareness Notes

Secure Surfing Use these recommended procedures to keep yourself secure when using the internet: 

•	Make use of secure websites (check the URL for "https://").

•	Steer clear of dubious links and pop-up advertisements.

•	Update your plugins and browser.

•	Turn on firewall protection and use a trustworthy antivirus program. 

•	When downloading software or data from unidentified sources, use caution. 

2. Hygiene of Passwords To safeguard your online accounts, you must use strong passwords. Here are some pointers:

•	Make use of a combination of special characters, numbers, capital and lowercase letters.

•	Steer clear of using information that can be guessed, such as names or birthdays. 

•	For each account, use a separate password. 

•	Regularly change your passwords. 

•	To create and maintain safe passwords, think about utilizing a password manager.

3. Security of Emails  Cyberattacks frequently use emails as a vector.  Keep yourself safe by adhering to these rules:  

• Never open emails from senders you are not familiar with.  

• Refrain from opening attachments from unreliable sources or clicking on dubious URLs.  

• Keep an eye out for phishing emails that contain urgent language and misspellings.  

• Before replying, confirm the sender’s email address.  

• Let your teacher or IT department know about any strange emails.

4. Synopsis of Typical Cyberthreats  You can identify and steer clear of typical cyberthreats by being aware of them:  

•	Phishing is the term for phony emails or communications that deceive you into divulging personal information.

•	 Malware is malicious software that is intended to harm or disable computers.

•	Malware that locks your files and demands money to unlock them is known as ransomware.

•	Spyware: Programs that surreptitiously collect data about you without your permission.

•	Social engineering is the practice of tricking someone into disclosing private information.

